      "Flavor": "- Yes, it smells like flowers, how some people buy a 100ct box of this \"Jasmine Blossom\" tea not knowing/understanding and then rate it poorly because of it is beyond me... it smells/tastes like every other Jasmine tea I've ever had, never felt it had an \"artificial\" taste to it. If you're used to drinking the jasmine \"pearls\" then it might not be as strong, but I've never experience the flavor to be \"bad\" as some others claim. **If you steep it in hot water for too long, of course it can get rather bitter. I recommend experimenting with steeping times if you aren't happy with the flavor. I don't have any issues when I cold brew overnight.** Be aware... Strength/taste not consistent between batches. - It is consistent within the box/batch, but between orders, some come stronger and some come a bit milder. Which might be expected, but if you've had the tea before and are expecting a specific strength/taste, just be aware that sometimes you might need to steep adjust steeping times or use more or less bags when making a batch. **I typically cold brew a pitcher, using 3-4 tea bags depending on the strength of the batch. If I hot brew a single cup, I only steep for a minute or two** Green tea - it is jasmine Green Tea... As far as I'm aware, all Jasmine tea is some sort of tea with jasmine added to it. Unless you are steeping legit jasmine flowers (can be bought as \"dried jasmine buds/petals\", not \"tea\") on your own, it's not likely you've ever gotten jasmine tea that didn't have actual tea leave in it... No staples - I've seen a few reviews from others about staples, I've never really thought about it since I've seen many different tea bags with staples since I was a kid. Plus, you'd expect them to use stainless steel, like the spoon you're likely using to stir your tea, or utensils you cook/eat with... In any case, this most recent batch I've gotten doesn't have any, so no need to worry about it if it were a concern. **I guess the concern 